user_prompt_template:
Two candidate submissions are checked out as subdirectories of the current working directory:
- Repository A at ./{dir_a}
- Repository B at ./{dir_b}

They are forks of a shared open-source baseline, so files common to both are expected and are not themselves evidence of copying. A deterministic file-level summary follows; use it to focus your reading:

{file_summary}

{runtime_context}

Use the Read, Glob and Grep tools to inspect the ACTUAL contents of the files under ./{dir_a} and ./{dir_b} — especially the files that differ — before deciding. Look through any renaming/reordering/reformatting to judge whether the two submissions are functionally the same.

Then decide whether A and B are the same functional submission (duplicate), genuinely distinct submissions (distinct), or whether the content is dominated by evasive padding/obfuscation designed to defeat this comparison (drop_evasion).

IMPORTANT — this verdict is published for public audit: in your reason, refer to the two submissions ONLY as "Repository A" and "Repository B". Do NOT mention the directory names, any repository URL, author, organisation, or GitHub username; cite file paths and code only.

Respond with ONLY a single JSON object and nothing else (no prose, no code fences):
{{"relationship": "duplicate" | "distinct" | "drop_evasion", "confidence": <number 0.0-1.0>, "reason": "<concise justification citing concrete code evidence, using only 'Repository A' / 'Repository B'>"}}
